BACKGROUND AND SUMMARY
n December 2014 Patient A, who was 86 years old at the time, was admitted to
Calvary Mater Newcastle Hospital, where Dr Barker was
a surgical registrar at
the time. Patient A had ongoing anaemia and rectal bleeding. On 28 December 2014
Dr Barker was requested
to band Patient A’s haemorrhoids. On examination,
Dr Barker noticed that the patient had a pedunculated polyp protruding from
anus. He invited a junior medical officer to perform a polypectomy procedure on
the ward to resect the polyp, and supervised
the procedure.
oon after cutting the polyp its stalk began to bleed, the endoloop being used
to hold the stalk of the polyp slipped and the stalk
retracted. In the course of
attempting to control the bleeding, Dr Barker was asked twice whether he would
like the assistance of
the hospital’s Rapid Response Team, but he declined
assistance. Dr Barker did not call for assistance from his supervising
Dr Adeeb Majid, however Dr Majid did come to arrive on the ward and assist in
attempting to stop the bleeding.
he attempts to locate the stalk and stop the bleeding were unsuccessful and
to the operating
theatre where she died.

A/Professor Anil Keshava. The
Commission’s complaint, which is the basis of the inquiry conducted by the
Committee, was based
upon A/Professor Keshava’s report.
hearing was held on 3 May 2018 when evidence was heard from A/Professor

THE RESPONDENT’S BACKGROUND
r Barker graduated with a Bachelor of Medicine/Bachelor of Surgery from the
University of Sydney in 2006. He worked as a senior resident
in surgery for a
number of hospitals in 2008 and from 2009 to 2015 he worked as a general
surgical trainee for a number of hospitals
including the Calvary Mater Newcastle
n 2015 he passed his fellowship exam and obtained his fellowship with the
Royal Australasian College of Surgeons in 2017. In that
year he was appointed a
Staff Specialist General Surgeon at Armidale Rural Referral Hospital. For a

He was deployed to the Middle East for about 6 months in 2012.
r Barker has no conditions on his practice of medicine.
THE LEGAL FRAMEWORK
he objectives of the national registration and accreditation scheme
established by the
Health Practitioner Regulation National Law (NSW)
National Law
) include to provide for the protection of the public by
ensuring that only health practitioners who are suitably trained and qualified
to practise in a competent and ethical manner are registered: s 3(2)(a). That
objective is not confined to protecting the patients
or potential patients of an
individual practitioner from any continuing risk of his or her malpractice or
incompetence. It also includes
protecting the public from similar misconduct or
incompetence by other practitioners, and upholding public confidence in the
of the profession:
Health Care Complaints Commission v Do
[2014] NSWCA 307
t is a guiding principle of the national registration and accreditation
scheme established by the National Law that restrictions on
the practice of the
medical profession are to be imposed under the scheme only if it is necessary to
ensure health services are provided
safely and are of an appropriate quality:
National Law s 3(c).
n exercising a function under the National Law, the Committee is required to
have regard to the objectives and guiding principles
of the national
registration and accreditation scheme established by the National Law (National
Law s 4), however, the protection
of the health and safety of the public must be
the Committee’s paramount consideration: National Law s 3A.
Unsatisfactory professional conduct
nsatisfactory professional conduct of a medical practitioner is defined in
the National Law to include the circumstances set out in
section 139B(1) of the
National Law. This definition includes, relevantly, conduct that demonstrates
the knowledge, skill or judgment
possessed, or care exercised, by the
practitioner in the practice of the practitioner’s profession is
significantly below the
standard reasonably expected
of a practitioner of an equivalent level of training or experience (National
Law s 139B(1)(a)).
he full text of section 139B of the National Law (NSW) and other relevant
provisions is attached to these reasons and marked as
Attachment 2
he phrase “significantly below the standard reasonably expected of a
practitioner of an equivalent level of training or experience”
defined in the National Law. However, in
Re A Medical Practitioner and the
Medical Practice Act
(unreported, NSWMT, 3 September 2007), Deputy
Chairperson Judge Freeman stated (in relation to legislation in the same terms
139B of the National Law) that “[a]s a general principle, the
use of the term ‘significant’ may in law be taken
to mean not
trivial, of importance, or substantial.”
Disciplinary powers of the Committee
he Committee may exercise the disciplinary powers conferred on it by section
146B of the National Law if it finds the subject-matter
of a complaint against a
relevant health practitioner to have been proved: National Law s 146A.
he subject matter of a complaint may be broader than individual particulars
of it, and may include the factual matters advanced in
support of it. The
Committee’s role is to conduct an inquiry into a complaint made against a
medical practitioner, informed
as it thinks necessary, and determining any
complaint it considers arises on the material before it. Subject to the
requirements
of procedural fairness, the Committee is not bound by the way in
which a complaint is particularised, or confined in the exercise
of its powers
to make findings and orders by strict reference to the terms of the complaint as
originally advanced:
Shuquan Liu v Health Care Complaints Commission
[2018] NSWSC 315
he purpose of an exercise of the Committee’s disciplinary powers is the
protection of the public and not to punish the practitioner:
Clyne v New
South Wales Bar Association
[1960] HCA 40
(1960) 104 CLR 186.
Nevertheless, imposing
restrictions on the practice of the medical profession by a medical
practitioner who has engaged in unsatisfactory
professional conduct operates as
a deterrent to the individual concerned and to the general body of medical
practitioners. Such restrictions
also maintain public confidence by signaling
that medical practitioners whose conduct does not meet the required standards of
medical profession will have restrictions placed on their registration.
he role of the Committee is to make findings on questions of fact in order to
determine whether the subject-matter of a complaint
has been proven on the
balance of probabilities (having regard to the principles discussed in
Briginshaw v Briginshaw
[1938] HCA 34
(1938) 60 CLR 336
361–362). Once that task has been completed, and the Committee has found
the subject-matter of a complaint
proven, the jurisdictional door to the discretionary powers in s 146B of the
National Law is open, and the Committee’s task
is to determine whether
and, if so, how, to exercise those discretionary powers.

submissions of the Commission and Dr Ruthnam. The material that the Committee

during the hearing of the inquiry. The Committee may not have referred directly

within these written reasons to all the evidence and submissions

to performing the polypectomy procedure on the ward;
he polypectomy procedure should have been performed in the operating theatre
or endoscopy suite.

he Macquarie Dictionary defines “profuse”, relevantly, as

s to sub-particular 2(g), the allegation that a second endoloop would have

Dr Barker also gave

t is unnecessary to reach a concluded view on whether the second endoloop,

satisfied that it could have. Nevertheless, the use of endoloops in this case

once the stalk of the polyp retracted it

APPROPRIATE ORDERS
n light of the views the Committee has reached above, the Committee must
consider how it can exercise its disciplinary powers to best
protect the health
and safety of the public.
onsistent with its protective purpose, the role of this Committee is to
determine whether Dr Barker presents a risk to the health
and safety of the
public as at the time of the Committee’s determination, not at the time at
which Dr Barker treated Patient
he question for the Committee is not simply whether Dr Barker should have
things differently in 2014, but, also, whether Dr Barker would do things
differently if he were presented with Patient A today. Any
actions taken since
2014 by Dr Barker to improve his practice of medicine are highly relevant to
that question.
n his statement of 20 March 2018 Dr Barker made the following comments:
“Since 28 December 2014, I have reflected at length on this sad and
unfortunate event.
In the days following the event I spoke extensively with my supervisors about
what had occurred and discussed the matter with Dr Pooshan
Navathe, the Director
of Medical Services at Maitland Hospital which is where I continued training
following the incident. As a result
of my involvement in the patient's care I
was required to undergo a term of active supervision from February 2015 to July
Maitland Hospital.
In January 2015, I participated in a Root Cause Analysis that was conducted
by the Area Health Service. I also presented and discussed
the incident at the
department Morbidity and Mortality Audit meeting.
I have reviewed the expert report of Associate Professor Keshava and I
accept the criticisms made about my conduct on 28 December
2014. I would not
perform a procedure such as this on the ward again and, with the benefit of
hindsight, I recognise that I could
have responded more effectively after the
endoloop slipped and the polyp stalk began bleeding and that it was becoming
less likely
as time went by that I would be able to locate the stalk on the
ward. Specifically, I should have agreed to a Rapid Response Team
call and/or
called Dr Majid earlier to request his assistance.
I accept that my management of [Patient A] after the endoloop slipped and she
began bleeding was significantly below the standard
expected of a practitioner
of an equivalent level of training or experience, as stated by Associate
Professor Keshava.
As a result of my reflection, discussion and active supervision I have taken
steps to improve and change my practice to avoid an incident
like this in the
future. I have improved my documentation and consent process and now take
considerably more caution when considering
whether it is appropriate to carry
out a procedure on the ward or as an outpatient.
Since the incident I have completed my general surgical training without
incident. I became a Fellow of the Royal Australasian College
of Surgeons in
2017 and was shortly thereafter appointed as a Staff Specialist General Surgeon
at Armidale Rural Referral Hospital.”

r Barker’s legal representative submitted that a caution was
appropriate in this case, but accepted that a reprimand was open
caution differs from a reprimand in that a reprimand is “an official
rebuke for past wrongful conduct, whereas a caution is
a reminder to take care
in the future and avoid repetition”:
Psychologists Board of Australia v
Coleman (Review and Regulation)
[2013] VCAT 738.
he failings demonstrated by Dr Barker in this case, many of which have been
admitted, were significant. Taking all of the above into
account, including the
seriousness of those failings, the Committee considers that a reprimand is
appropriate.
s to other protective orders, the Committee notes that the events in question
occurred three and a half years ago, and that since
that time Dr Barker has
obtained his fellowship and a position as a staff specialist. The referee
statements and Dr Barker’s
evidence about his current workplace suggest
that he already has sufficient mentors available to him. In these circumstances,
Committee does not consider that any protective orders requiring mentorship
are necessary.
owever, the Committee does consider that conditions requiring further
education are appropriate, given that the essence of Dr Barker’s
in this case related to poor decision-making on his part, including the
following decisions:
erforming the polypectomy on the ward;
he use of endoloops in performing the polypectomy;
efusal of the offer of assistance from the Rapid Response Team;
ailure to call for assistance from his supervising surgeon earlier.
n light of this, the Committee considers that further structured training
around clinical decision making is warranted and appropriate.
The Committee
considers the Clinical Decision Making course run by the Royal Australasian
College of Surgeons to be the most appropriate
course, as it includes tools
“developed as a means to address poor clinical decision making processes,
particularly as a guide
for the supervisor dealing
with a struggling trainee or as a self improvement exercise”:
https://www.surgeons.org/for-health-professionals/register-courses-
events/professional-development/clinical-decision-making/.
he Committee notes that the course is not being run in New South Wales before
the end of 2018, and that Dr Barker performs an important
role at a regional
hospital that ought not be compromised due to the need to travel outside the
State. As a result, the Committee
has imposed a longer timeframe in which to
allow Dr Barker to participate in the course than may otherwise be appropriate.
Nevertheless,
the Committee encourages Dr Barker to participate in the course
this calendar year, if that will not compromise the level of care
provided at
his current workplace.
